   programming knowledge and technical skill rather than creativity and usefulness

   Step 1:
    Creating a Graph

   You can create a Graph by copying the Template.json and adding you own nodes/vertices & connections/edges
   but what does each value do?
   lets see here...
   {
  "directed": false,
  "algorithm": "spring",
  "V": ["Bob","Josh","Mary"],
  "E": [
      ["Bob","Josh"]
      ,["Josh","Mary"]
      ,["Mary","Bob"]
      ]
    }

  directed -> it specifies whether the graph is a Directed Graph,or a Undirected Graph (DG & UG for short)
  algorithm -> specifies which algorithm to use when positioning the nodes
  usable algorithms:

  -arf
  -bipartite
  -bfs
  -circular
  -forceatlas2
  -kamada_kawai
  -planar
  -random
  -shell
  -spring
  -spiral

   The best ones to use (in my humble opinion) are "kamada_kawai" and "planar" BUT if you want a default one for all use-cases,use "spring"

   V -> this is the list of vertices you can add to your graph,currently,due to not having built some type of converter,most people (unless you make a converter)
   have to fill this in by hand

   E -> Same with V But the difference is it stores the EDGES of the graph ("connections"),withouth those,your nodes are lonely


   That's it about hte Graph JSON,pretty simple


   Step 2:
        Adding our Graph

     To add the graph,you simply have to drag it into the "Graphs" Folder,there's some pre-made graphs there,for demo and testing purposes

   Step 3:
        Tweaking the rules

     By now,you might have realised that there's a JSON file called "rules"
    this files is the most important document in the entire tool.

    This file dictates (When Selecting to use Presets) how the programm functions.
    It's main purpose is:
        - Determine the Algorithms for placing/painting nodes
        - Customizability of the programm
        - Research/Testing

    and so,it's crucial you do NOT delete it (you can redownload it,but still)
   in another part,i'll explain what each rule does.

